{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1938010201/0383.xml":{"full_text":"STORE SALES GAIN\nIN WEEK AND TEAR\nRetail Trade in Capital and\nFifth District Is Ahead\nof 1936.\nRetail trade in Washington for\nthe week ending Wednesday, Decern*\nber 29, registered a sharp increase of\n30.82 per cent over the corresponding\nweek a year ago, the Commerce De\npartment reported in a summary cov\nering 38 key cities. The comparison,\nhowever, is a five-day week with a\nfour-day w'eek last year.\nComparison with the previous week\nshows a decrease of 59 per cent, as the\nfive-day week is compared with the\nsix shopping days in the previous\nperiod.\nRetail trade in the whole fifth Re\nserve district, which includes Wash\nington. is expected to reveal a mod\nerate increase over 1936 for the full\nyear, the Commerce report states. The\ndistrict as a whole also scored a\nslight gain last w'eek over the same\nweek a year ago.\nBatimore\u2019s retail volume will un\ndoubtedly show an advance for the\nfull year over 1936, the report said.\nSo will Richmond and Norfolk. Busi\nness in Charleston, S. C.. will be up\nfrom 5 to 10 per cent for the full year.\nReports to the Department of Com\nmerce from many cities outside this\ntrade area reveal that the closing days\nof 1937 brought unexpected gains in\nsales volumes. Post-Christmas busi\nness in many cities proved a pleasant\nsurprise, the survey adds.\n\nDenver Rio Grande Western\nR. R \u2014Deficit, 11 months ended No\nvember 30, was $5,431,762, against\ndeficit of $3,725,110,\nDECLINE IN TIN PRICE\nAPPEARS NEAR ITS ENE\nBy Cambrldse Associate*.\nWith quotas for the first quarter o:\n1938 fixed by the International Tir\nCommittee at 70 per cent of standarc\ntonnages, there seems little proepeci\nfor further decrease In the price oi\ntin.\nThe decline now has brought prices\ndown 33 per cent from the year\u2019s high\nand the adjustment move appears\ncompleted.\nThe world's visible supply of tin\nis at present materially under the\naverage for the last decade.\nAny lifting of previously depress\ning factors will find tin In a strong\nstatistical position.\nStability at or near current levels\nis likely pending the general business\nrevival to which tin will be quickly\nresponsive.\nD.C. SECURITIES\n'Suptflion* by Johnston. Lemon A Co\nwiV \u00abl5d \u00a3?ked ouo'\u00bb,\u2018<>ns for the\nT!!fr. on Washington securities which\nare traded over-the-counter follow;\nBONDS.\nBarber A Ross deb. 4s 1845 *5d' A3pnd\nCons. Title Co. Inc. Hs 1851 inn\nD. C Paper MU! Is* 3s 1840 05\nHamilton Rt Corp. 1st 5s 45 83 87\nMayfl. Hotel Corp. 1st 5s'50 72\u2018j 7HU\nNatl Press Ble. 1st 3.5s \u201950 04 up\nRacquet Club 1st 5s 18*5 47\nRiverside APts. 1st 7s 1834 80 loot*\nWash. Auditorium 1st Os '44 05 75\nWash. Properties Inc. 7s '55 42 47\nSTOCKS.\nAnacostia Bank _ _ 150\nAnacostia Finance su,\nBarber A; Ross pfd. (new)I_ 7\nCity Bank it\nColumbia National Bank \u201cI 200\nCons. Titla Corp, pfd _ 42 47\nCons Title Corp. com. __ fii* 10\nEast Wash. Savinas Bank 1412\nFederal American Co pfd. 3\"\nFederal American Co. com. Pi\nHamilton National Bank 27 so\nInternational Financr Units 13\nLincoln Hall Association 75\nMerchants' Tr. A Stor. pfd. 17\nMerchants' Tr A Stor. com. 14\nNational Capital Insurance 1R\nNatl. Mtge. A Invest, pfd p, \">i\nNational Metropolitan Bank 225 2\u00ab0\nRaleigh Hotel com. an\nReal ESt. M. A Guar. com.. P4\nSecurity Sav. A Commercial 142 175\nS th 11 Oxygen Co com. new 30\nUnion Finance Units *\"1\nUnion Trust Co. 85 inn\nWashington Base Ball Club' 35\nWash. Convention Hall pfd 35\nWash. Properties Inc. v.t c 1\nWASHINGTON STOCK EXCHANGE\nYEAR 1937\n(Reported by W. B. Hibbs A Co., Hibbs Building. Washington. D. C.)\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE WASHINGTON STOCK EXCHANGE UP TO AND INCLUDING\nFRIDAY, DECEMBER 31, IP37.\nBONDS. Annrn*\nPtTBLIC W1LITW. Open. High. Low. dosa. yield\nS22.000 Ana A Pot Riv R R 1st 5% 1949_ 77 77 go go n 10*\n6 000 Ana A Po